Name: blogcatalog
Description: Network of social relationships of online bloggers. The vertex labels represent interests of the bloggers.

Name: homosapiens
Description: Subgraph of the PPI network for Homo Sapiens. The labels are obtained from the hallmark gene sets and represent biological states.

Name: wikipos
Description: Co-occurrence network of words appearing in the first million bytes of the Wikipedia dump. The labels are the Part-of-Speech (POS) tags inferred by Stanford POS-Tagger

Name: enron
Ultimate source: Jitesh Shetty and Jafar Adibi. The enron email dataset database schema and brief statistical report. Information sciences institute technical report, University of Southern California, 4(1):120–128, 2004.
Description: Email correspondence dataset containing around 50K emails exchanged among　employees of the ENRON energy company over a three-year period. If you really want to see the original data see http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~enron/ and click May 7, 2015 Version of dataset.

Name: unvote
Ultimate source: Erik Voeten, Anton Strezhnev, and Michael Bailey. United Nations General Assembly Voting Data, 2009. URL https://doi.org/10.7910/DVN/LEJUQZ.
Description: Roll-call votes in the United Nations General Assembly from 1946 to 2020. If two nations both voted "yes" for an item, then the edge weight between them is incremented by one

Name: untrade
Ultimate source: Graham K MacDonald, Kate A Brauman, Shipeng Sun, Kimberly M Carlson, Emily S Cassidy, James S Gerber, and Paul C West. Rethinking agricultural trade relationships in an era of globalization. BioScience, 65(3):275–289, 2015.
Description: Directed, food and agriculture trading graph between 181 nations and spanning over 30 years. The edge weights specify the total sum of normalized agriculture import or export values between two countries.

Name: uslegis_net
Ultimate source: James H Fowler. Legislative cosponsorship networks in the us house and senate. Social networks, 28(4):454–465, 2006.
Description: The projected graph is a weighted undirected graph representing how many times each pair of nodes co-appears in a simplex. PROBABLY YOU CAN MAKE A DYNAMIC VERSION OF THIS ONE.

Name: uslegis_net_small_dyn
Ultimate source: James H Fowler. Legislative cosponsorship networks in the us house and senate. Social networks, 28(4):454–465, 2006.
Description: Dynamic Senate co-sponsorship graph which documents social interactions between legislators from the US Senate. The edge weights specify the number of times two congress persons have co-sponsored a bill in a given congress.

Name: uslegis_net_dyn
Ultimate source: James H Fowler. Legislative cosponsorship networks in the us house and senate. Social networks, 28(4):454–465, 2006.
Description: Dynamic Senate co-sponsorship graph which documents social interactions between legislators from the US Senate. The edge weights specify the number of times two congress persons have co-sponsored a bill in a given congress.

Name: uslegis_hyp
Ultimate source: James H Fowler. Legislative cosponsorship networks in the us house and senate. Social networks, 28(4):454–465, 2006.

Name: contacts
Ultimate source: Piotr Sapiezynski, Arkadiusz Stopczynski, David Dreyer Lassen, and Sune Lehmann. Interaction data from the copenhagen networks study. Scientific Data, 6(1):1–10, 2019.
Description: Temporal evolution of the physical proximity around 700 university students over a period of four weeks. Each participant is assigned an unique ID and edges between users indicate that they are within close proximity of each other. The edge weights indicate the physical proximity between participants.

Name: dawn_net
Ultimate source: Austin R. Benson, Rediet Abebe, Michael T. Schaub, Ali Jadbabaie, and Jon Kleinberg.　Simplicial closure and higher-order link prediction.Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS), 2018.
Description: Projected version of below

Name: dawn_hyp
Ultimate source: Austin R. Benson, Rediet Abebe, Michael T. Schaub, Ali Jadbabaie, and Jon Kleinberg.　Simplicial closure and higher-order link prediction.Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS), 2018.
Description: This dataset comes from the Drug Abuse Warning Network (DAWN), which tracks drug-related hospital emergency visits in the U.S. Each simplex represents the drugs reported by a patient during an emergency visit, encompassing illicit drugs, prescription medications, over-the-counter drugs, and dietary supplements. Timestamps are given in quarter-years over an 8-year span (2004-2011), encoded as (year * 4 + quarter).

Name: ndc_net
Ultimate source: Austin R. Benson, Rediet Abebe, Michael T. Schaub, Ali Jadbabaie, and Jon Kleinberg.　Simplicial closure and higher-order link prediction.Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS), 2018.
Description: Projected version of below

Name: ndc_hyp
Ultimate source: Austin R. Benson, Rediet Abebe, Michael T. Schaub, Ali Jadbabaie, and Jon Kleinberg.　Simplicial closure and higher-order link prediction.Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS), 2018.
Description: This dataset represents a sequence of timestamped simplices from the U.S. FDA's National Drug Code (NDC) Directory. Each simplex corresponds to a drug's NDC code, with nodes being the substances in the drug. Timestamps, in days, indicate when the drug was first marketed.

Name: coauthor_net
Ultimate source: Austin R. Benson, Rediet Abebe, Michael T. Schaub, Ali Jadbabaie, and Jon Kleinberg.　Simplicial closure and higher-order link prediction.Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS), 2018.
Description: Projected version of below

Name: coauthor_hyp
Ultimate source: Austin R. Benson, Rediet Abebe, Michael T. Schaub, Ali Jadbabaie, and Jon Kleinberg.　Simplicial closure and higher-order link prediction.Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS), 2018.
Description: This dataset is a sequence of timestamped simplices from the DBLP database, where each simplex represents a publication. In this context, nodes are authors and the timestamps indicate the publication year. The resulting graph shows how often each pair of authors collaborated, with edges weighted by the number of collaborations.

Name: wiod2016
Ultimate source: Timmer, M. P., Dietzenbacher, E., Los, B., Stehrer, R. and de Vries, G. J. (2015), "An Illustrated User Guide to the World Input–Output Database: the Case of Global Automotive Production" , Review of International Economics ., 23: 575–605
Description: The World Input-Output Database (WIOD) November 2016 Release provides data for 28 EU countries and 15 other major global countries, spanning from 2000 to 2014.

Name: wiod2013
Ultimate source: Timmer, M. P., Dietzenbacher, E., Los, B., Stehrer, R. and de Vries, G. J. (2015), "An Illustrated User Guide to the World Input–Output Database: the Case of Global Automotive Production" , Review of International Economics ., 23: 575–605
Description: The 2013 Release of the World Input-Output Database (WIOD) includes data for 27 EU countries and 13 other significant global nations, covering the years 1995 to 2011.

Name: wiodlong
Ultimate source: Woltjer, P., Gouma, R. and Timmer, M. P. (2021), "Long-run World Input-Output Database: Version 1.1 Sources and Methods", GGDC Research Memorandum 190
Description: The Long-run World Input–Output Database (WIOD) offers yearly data from 1965-2000, a time marked by swift global economic growth and heightened integration of production and consumption. It captures the inclusion of countries like Japan and South Korea, as well as the ongoing unification of nations within the European Union, into the world economy.

Name: ethereum
Ultimate source: Ferenc Béres; István András Seres; András A. Benczúr; Mikerah Quintyne-Collins Blockchain is Watching You: Profiling and Deanonymizing Ethereum Users
Description: A subset of Ethereum transactions is presented. It's worth noting that even if there are transactions between two entities using smart contracts, the weights could still be 0 (https://ethereum.stackexchange.com/questions/138267/why-is-ether-value-0-but-the-contract-specifies-over-500-ether-were-transferred). If you wish to overlook this detail, simply disregard the weights entirely.

Name: bitcoinalpha
Ultimate source: Kumar, Srijan and Spezzano, Francesca and Subrahmanian, VS and Faloutsos, Christos, Edge weight prediction in weighted signed networks, Data Mining (ICDM), 2016 IEEE 16th International Conference on, 2016
Description: members rate others on a scale from -10 (complete distrust) to +10 (complete trust), making it the first research-available weighted signed directed network.

Name: bitcoinotc
Ultimate source: Kumar, Srijan and Spezzano, Francesca and Subrahmanian, VS and Faloutsos, Christos, Edge weight prediction in weighted signed networks, Data Mining (ICDM), 2016 IEEE 16th International Conference on, 2016
Description: members rate others on a scale from -10 (complete distrust) to +10 (complete trust), making it the first research-available weighted signed directed network.

Name: court_500
Description: We offer data on court opinion citations. Our dataset specifically focuses on court opinions that have been cited more than 500 times. Both the publication date and the specific court identifier for each opinion can be found in the nodes.csv file. For a more detailed review of individual cases, simply search for the identifier on Google. If you need the full text of any opinion, please let us know, and we can incorporate it into the dataset.
